      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the math.\n\nThe interest on a declining balance loan is calculated using the formula:\n\nInterest = Outstanding Balance x Interest Rate x Time Period\n\nIn this case, the time period is usually a month, and the interest rate is a monthly rate (e.g., 6%/year ÷ 12 months = 0.5%/month).\n\nTo calculate the interest, you multiply the outstanding balance by the interest rate and the time period. For example, if your outstanding balance is $9,900 and the interest rate is 0.5%/month, the interest would be:\n\nInterest = $9,900 x 0.005 x 1 (month) = $49.50\n\nThis interest is then added to the outstanding balance, making the new balance:\n\nNew Balance = $9,900 + $49.50 = $10,049.50\n\nNow, when you make a payment of $100, the interest is calculated on the new balance of $10,049.50, which is:\n\nInterest = $10,049.50 x 0.005 x 1 (month) = $50.25\n\nYour new balance would be",
